# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: problem-details-rfc
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] In computing, **content negotiation** refers to mechanisms defined as a part of HTTP that make it possible to serve different versions of a document (or more generally, representations of a resource) at the same URI, so that user agents can specify which version fits their capabilities the best.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] One classical use of this mechanism is to serve an image in GIF or PNG format, so that a browser that cannot display PNG images (e.g.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] MS Internet Explorer 4) will be served the GIF version.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] A resource may be available in several different representations; for example, it might be available in different languages or different media types.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] One way of selecting the most appropriate choice is to give the user an index page and let them select the most appropriate choice; however it is often possible to automate the choice based on some selection criteria.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] HTTP provides for several different content negotiation mechanisms including: server-driven (or proactive), agent-driven (or reactive), transparent, and/or hybrid combinations thereof.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] Server-driven or proactive content negotiation is performed by algorithms on the server which choose among the possible variant representations.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] This is commonly performed based on user agent-provided acceptance criteria.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] To summarize how this works, when a user agent submits a request to a server, the user agent informs the server what media types or other aspects of content presentation it understands with ratings of how well it understands them.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] More precisely, the user agent provides HTTP headers that lists acceptable aspects of the resource and quality factors for them.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] The server is then able to supply the version of the resource that best fits the user agent's needs.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] Where the 'q' - quality - factor for German is higher than that for English.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] Multiple HTTP headers are often supplied together for content format or, specifically media type, language and a few other aspects of a resource.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] In addition to the commonly used `Accept` header for Media Type, the `Accept-Language` header for language negotiation, RFC 7231 also describes `Accept-Charset` & `Accept-Encodings` for character encodings and content codings (compression) respectively.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] Neither RFC 7231 nor the more recent related specifications such as *Content Negotiation by Profile* specify how to resolve trade-offs in cases where different headers specify conflicting requirements, such as, in the above example, choosing between an HTML page in English and a GIF image in German.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] Agent-driven or reactive content negotiation is performed by algorithms in the user-agent which choose among the possible variant representations.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] This is commonly performed based on a server provided list of representations and metadata about them.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] To summarize how this works, when a user agent submits a request to a server, the server informs the user-agent which representations it has available as well as any metadata it has about each representation (e.g., content-type, quality, language, etc.).
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] The user-agent then resubmits the request to a specific URL for the chosen representation.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] This can be automatically chosen by the user-agent or the user-agent can present the user with the choices and the user can directly choose such.
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] More precisely, the server responds with either 300 Multiple Choices or 406 Not Acceptable (when server-driven, user-agent acceptance criteria are provided but the server cannot automatically make a selection).
[src:problem-details-rfc/content-negotiation] Unfortunately HTTP leaves the format of the list of representations and metadata along with selection mechanisms unspecified.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:problem-details-rfc/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] This article lists standard and notable non-standard HTTP response status codes.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] Standardized codes are defined by IETF as documented in Request for Comments (RFC) publications and maintained by the IANA.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] Other, non-standard values are used by various servers.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] The descriptive text after the numeric code – the *reason phrase* – is shown here with typical value, but in practice, can be different or omitted.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] Status codes defined by IETF are listed below.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] Emphasized terms *must*, *must not* and *should* are interpretation guidelines as given by RFC 2119.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] An informational response indicates that the request was received and understood and is being processed.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] It alerts the client to wait for a final response.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] As the HTTP/1.0 standard did not define any 1xx status codes, servers *must not* send a 1xx response to an HTTP/1.0 compliant client except under experimental conditions.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] Sending a large request body to a server after a request has been rejected for inappropriate headers would be inefficient.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] status code in response before sending the body.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] If the client receives an error code such as 403 (Forbidden) or 405 (Method Not Allowed) then it should not send the request's body.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] header as it indicates that the server does not support expectations (this is the case, for example, of HTTP/1.0 servers).
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] The requester has asked the server to switch protocols and the server has agreed to do so.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] A WebDAV request may contain many sub-requests involving file operations, requiring a long time to complete the request.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] This code indicates that the server has received and is processing the request, but no response is available yet.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] This prevents the client from timing out and assuming the request was lost.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] Used to return some response headers before final HTTP message.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] A success status indicates that the action requested by the client was received, understood, and accepted.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] Standard response for successful HTTP requests.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] In a GET request, the response will contain an entity corresponding to the requested resource.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] In a POST request, the response will contain an entity describing or containing the result of the action.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] The request has been fulfilled, resulting in the creation of a new resource.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] The request has been accepted for processing, but the processing has not been completed.
[src:problem-details-rfc/list-of-http-status-codes] The request might or might not be eventually acted upon, and may be disallowed when processing occurs.
